data.name: Kanō Jigorō
data.description:
Jigoro Kano (嘉納 治五郎, 10 December 1860 – 4 May
1938[3]) was a Japanese educator, athlete, and the founder of
Judo. Along with Ju-Jutsu, Judo was one of the first Japanese
martial arts to gain widespread international recognition, and the
first to become an official Olympic sport. Pedagogical innovations
attributed to Kanō include the use of black and white belts, and
the introduction of dan ranking to show the relative ranking among
members of a martial art style. Well-known mottoes attributed to
Kanō include "good use of energy" (精力善用 seiryoku zen'yō) and
"mutual welfare and benefit" (自他共栄 jita kyōei).
